description.plain:
Marvin Gaye was one of the most consistent and enigmatic of the Motown hitmakers, with a career that exemplified the maturation of black pop into a sophisticated form spanning social and sexual politics. Blessed with a mellifluous tenor and a four-octave vocal range, Gaye was among the most gifted composers and singers of his era.

Gaye started his recording career in the late 1950s as a member of the doo-wop group the Moonglows, though he left and moved to Detroit to sign to Motown in 1961. Gaye wanted to become a crooner in the vein of Frank Sinatra and Nat King Cole, while Motown founder Berry Gordy pushed him to go in a more R&B direction. His first album, 1961’s The Soulful Moods of Marvin Gaye, had a mix of both styles and flopped.

In 1962, Gaye landed his first hit with the driving R&B of “Stubborn Kind of Fellow”; this started a string of uptempo singles like “Hitch Hike”, “Pride & Joy” and “Can I Get a Witness”. Slower tunes such as “How Sweet It Is (To Be Loved By You)” positioned him as a handsome ladies' man. In the latter half of the 1960s, he released several successful singles with Smokey Robinson, including the top 10 hits “I’ll Be Doggone” and “Ain’t That Peculiar”, before uniting with producer Norman Whitfield.

In 1967, Gaye recorded the paranoid “I Heard It Through the Grapevine” with Whitfield, which Motown shelved. Whitfield rearranged the tune significantly for Gladys Knight & the Pips, whose version reached #2. Gaye’s version was released a year later and became the biggest hit of his career, staying at #1 for seven weeks and topping the UK charts.

Gaye also recorded a series of successful duets with female artists, including Mary Wells (“Once Upon a Time”, “What’s the Matter with You Baby”), Kim Weston (“It Takes Two”), and Diana Ross (Diana & Marvin). However, his late ‘60s partnership with Tammi Terrell was the most enduring and successful. Their first duet, “Ain’t No Mountain High Enough” is the oldest song with one billion Spotify streams. Her premature death in 1970, aged 24 from a brain tumour, devastated Gaye and caused him to take a brief hiatus.

In 1971, Marvin Gaye marked a creative rebirth with the socially-conscious “What’s Going On”, which he produced and co-wrote. Gordy did not like the song, and Motown staff released the single behind his back. When the single became an unexpected hit, he gave Gaye a week to record the rest of the album. The resulting What’s Going On LP addresses social injustice, the environment, spirituality and drug use, and was a critical and commercial success. “Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)” and “Inner City Blues (Makes Me Wanna Holler” were Top 10 hits, and Rolling Stone named What’s Going On as the greatest album of all time in 2020.

After composing the soundtrack for the blaxploitation film Trouble Man, Gaye shifted from social to sexual with 1973’s Let’s Get It On. The title track became his second #1 hit, and much of the album was sparked by his infatuation with Janis Hunter, a girl he had met during recording sessions. The album’s closer, “Just to Keep You Satisfied”, described the end of his marriage with Anna Gordy Gaye. Let’s Get It On was his highest-charting album on the Billboard 200, peaking at #2.

Gaye’s intensifying relationship with Hunter inspired his 1976 album I Want You, which is perhaps his most explicit. Leon Ware had originally written most of the songs for himself, but was persuaded to let Gaye record them. In 1977, he recorded the one-off disco number “Got to Give It Up”, which became his third and final #1 single.

During this time, Gaye was facing significant legal trouble in his divorce from Anna, and agreed to give her half of his next album’s royalties as part of his divorce payment. In 1978, he released the double album Here, My Dear, which spoke about their divorce in extreme detail. The album was a critical and commercial failure at the time, but has received significant reappraisal in the decades since.

Gaye entered a personal slump, but started sessions for a more party-focused album called Love Man. Sessions were broken by his exile to Hawai'i, but upon his return, he shifted it to a more  ambitious and self-exploratory work named In Our Lifetime?. However, an impatient band member took Gaye’s unfinished tapes to Motown, who remixed and released them in 1981. A furious Gaye responded by ending his 20-year contract with Motown and signing with CBS.

For his next album, Gaye moved to Ostend, Belgium to clean up his drug usage and focus on recording. While biographer David Ritz was visiting, he noticed several S&M drawing books on Gaye’s table and said, “You need some sexual healing.” This line inspired his 1982 comeback smash “Sexual Healing”, which won Gaye the only two Grammys he would receive in his lifetime. Its success made Midnight Love one of the best-selling albums of his career. Midnight Love introduced a more synthetic sound, making heavy use of the Roland TR-808 drum machine.

With this success, Gaye returned to the US to live with his parents and reportedly became extremely depressed and paranoid. His life ended tragically on April 1, 1984, one day before his 45th birthday, when he was shot to death by his father. Marvin intervened in an argument between his parents and hit his father, who then pulled out the gun Marvin had gifted him for Christmas.

Gaye remains one of the most beloved and influential artists in popular music, and has been referenced and sampled prominently in the decades since. Artists like Janet Jackson, Sade, Maxwell and D'Angelo have cited Gaye as a key musical influence.

songs.full_title: Sexual Healing by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Sexual Healing

description.plain:
Released in 1982, “Sexual Healing” is one of Marvin Gaye’s most popular songs, and his last to reach the top 20 in the US, UK and Australia. It won the Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Perfomance and the instrumental version won Best R&B Instrumental Perfomance. In 2003, Rolling Stone listed it as one of the best songs of all time.

Recorded in Ostend, Belgium in 1982, the song represented a comeback for Marvin to the American music scene. The singer had been living overseas to escape two divorces, tax scandals and to overcome a debilitating cocaine addiction and depression. The  song was borne out of a comment made by songwriter David Ritz’s when he visited Gaye and saw he had pornography spread across his coffee table:

‘Marvin, this is some sick [expletive]. What are you doing? What you really need is sexual healing.’

A plaque commemorating Marvin Gaye’s stay in Ostend, Belgium, was placed in front of the apartment where he lived.

songs.full_title: Let's Get It On by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Let’s Get It On

description.plain:
“Let’s Get It On” is a deceptively simple declaration of sex-positivity, released at a time when such statements were revolutionary.  It is even more impressive when one considers that it was created by a man awakening from the trauma of growing up constantly physically and emotionally abused by a preacher father who conditioned his children to regard sex as shameful.  That father, Marvin Gaye Sr., would infamously murder his son in 1984.

The song celebrates a turning point for the younger Marvin, who first learned to play music in the church and at one point endeavored to follow in his father’s footsteps as a minister.

In “Let’s Get It On,” Marvin is still making spiritual music, but this time to elevate the act of physical love and exalt it as an expression of a living person’s potential on Earth.

It topped both the US Pop and R&B charts in the summer of 1973 and was also successful in Canada and the UK.

description.plain:
“Inner City Blues” depicts the ghettos of inner-city America as it discusses the bleak economic situation set against the backdrop of the space race, the Vietnam War and the subsequent protests it caused as well as police brutality. It peaked at #9 in the US in late 1971.

“Inner City Blues” stands in stark contrast to What’s Going On’s mostly uplifting tone as it uses darker, mellow funk sounds to capture the suffering spirit of urban America.

description.plain:
“I Heard It Through the Grapevine” was originally a song written by Norman Whitfield and Barrett Strong for Motown Records in 1966, and made famous by Marvin Gaye in a single released in October 1968 on Motown’s Tamla label.

Originally recorded by Smokey Robinson & the Miracles in 1966, that version was rejected by Motown owner Berry Gordy, who told Whitfield and Strong to make it stronger. After recording the song with Marvin Gaye in 1967, which Gordy also rejected, Whitfield produced a version with Gladys Knight & the Pips, which Gordy agreed to release as a single in September 1967, and which went to number two on the Billboard chart. The Marvin Gaye version was placed on his 1968 album In the Groove, where it gained the attention of radio disc jockeys, and Gordy finally agreed to its release as a single in October 1968, when it went to the top of the Billboard Pop Singles chart for seven weeks from December 1968 to January 1969 and became for a time the biggest hit single on the Motown label.

songs.full_title: I Want You by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: I Want You

description.plain:
“I Want You” is the lead single off of the 1976 album of the same name that would go on to become one of Marvin Gaye’s most successful records.

Having struggled to come up with material since releasing Let’s Get it On, Marvin teamed up with fellow Motown musician Leon Ware to help him write and produce the record. Ware initially composed much of the music in the same vein as his own similarly erotic-themed album, Musical Massage, with low-key production and steamy after-the-party beats and vocals.



I Want You, however, evolved into a sensual autobiographical narrative centered around Marvin’s real life love affair with Janis Hunter. Marvin and Janis met in 1973  which influenced his music from Let’s Get it On until the end of his career. I Want You’s lyrical content is heavily based on his attraction to a woman whom he initially asks for reciprocated love from, then to live, feel his love and dance with him. The sentiment is delivered so passionately that Marvin calls Janis’s name throughout the album in different songs.



As author Michael Eric Dyson wrote in his book, Mercy, Mercy Me: The Art, Loves, and Demons of Marvin Gaye:

I Want You is unmistakably a work of romantic and erotic tribute to the woman he deeply loved and would marry shortly, Janis Hunter. Gaye’s obsession with the woman in her late teens is nearly palpable in the sensual textures that are the album’s aural and lyrical signature. Their relationship was relentlessly passionate and emotionally rough-hewn; they played up each other’s strengths, and played off each other’s weaknesses.

songs.full_title: Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology) by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)

description.plain:
This song mourns the destruction of the environment in a modernized society. Oil catastrophies, radioactive waste, and overpopulation… we even Almost Lost Detroit.

In his biography Divided Soul, Marvin said:

When we don’t follow [Jesus'] example and turn to exploitation and greed, we destroy ourselves. That’s what ‘Mercy Mercy Me’ is about.

It was recorded in 1971, when the public’s awareness of environmentalism was at an all-time high. Imagine how mortified Gaye would have been if he had seen what was going to happen to the environment during the next 40 years …

songs.full_title: Got to Give It Up by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Got to Give It Up

description.plain:
“Got to Give it Up” chronicles the nervy night of a man too shy to get out there on the dance floor and let loose. It’s only once he gives in – or Gives it Up – to the rhythm and finds himself a partner to groove with that he starts to enjoy himself. The song’s lyrics were inspired by Marvin Gaye’s documented stage fright and anxiety that afflicted him throughout his career during performances.

The song became a No. 1 hit in 1977 and propelled the live performance album it was released on, Live at the London Palladium, to an impressive two million sales.

“Got to Give it Up” became the subject of a resurgence of public interest after Marvin Gaye’s estate was awarded $7.4 million in damages in a 2015 lawsuit that found Robin Thicke and Pharrell Williams guilty of breaching copyright for their incorporation of the song into their hit single “Blurred Lines”.

As David Ritz, Marvin Gaye’s biographer, wrote in Rolling Stone in 2013:

The vast majority of those singers – with Thicke standing as the most recent example – are so eager to emulate Marvin’s lush sensuality that they miss the single ingredient that lends Marvin’s artistry its spiritual power: his nuanced sense of autobiographical storytelling. Take “Got to Give It Up.” Like “Blurred Lines,” it was an across-the-board Number One hit. Marvin wrote it in 1976 at the height of the disco craze. Rather than follow the craze, he fought the craze, crafting an idiosyncratic groove completely foreign from the four-on-the-floor beat that typified disco. Even more radical was the story he told on top of the beat – a tale of a man, much like Marvin, who’s deadly afraid of dancing. Gaye paints the portrait of a wallflower “too nervous to really get down,” a shy guy whose “body yearned to be free.” The song becomes a vehicle to face his fear. And the infectious groove allows him to overcome the fear.

It’s only once he gives in – or Gives it Up – to the rhythm and finds himself a partner to groove with that he starts to enjoy himself. songs.title: Trouble Man

description.plain:
After Isaac Hayes hit it big with his Oscar-winning “Theme from Shaft” in 1971, every soul singer worth his salt wanted to try his hand at producing a hit soundtrack for a “blaxploitation” film. Marvin Gaye was no exception and came out with the soundtrack to the 20th Century Fox film Trouble Man in 1972. The title track, which became a #4 R&B hit single, describes a stereotypical 70s black action hero who came up hard in the ghetto and has to play by his own rules to survive.



The song enjoyed a resurgence in popularity after its use in Captain America: Winter Soldier. Falcon refers to the album after Captain America asks how to catch up on the past 70 years, telling him it’s “everything you missed jammed into one album.”

A live recording was issued as a single in 1974. The live version of the song was Gaye’s most successful single during the three-year gap between Let’s Get It On and his following 1976 album, I Want You.

songs.full_title: God Is Love by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: God Is Love

description.plain:
Track 5 on What’s Going On, an album which on July 22, 2013, was certified platinum by the British Phonographic Industry for shipments of 300,000 albums.



In this song, Marvin makes a return of sorts to his religious background dedicating the song to God and his father, Marvin Gay, Sr. who later shot him.



He takes the track’s title from 1 John 4.



The original 45 version of “What’s Going On” included a slower, string-laden version of this song as its b-side. But the album version is more joyous and faster.

songs.full_title: Right On by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Right On

description.plain:
Marvin Gaye was many things. A chronicler of the times, a believer, a sexual healer and a superstar musician but, above all else, he was a man who aimed to touch the souls of people around the world. “Right On” is his cry of support for those who find compassion in their hearts and do what they can to help their fellow man.

While What’s Going On follows a concurrent style that allows each track to bleed into the next, giving it the illusion of one lengthy song, “Right On” has a distinctively Latin soul sound to it. It is also the longest song on the album.

Reviewing   What’s Going On’s 40th Anniversary Edition, Ryan Dombal wrote:

Perhaps this smooth front also has to do with the fact that Gaye was “hardly an activist in the traditional sense,” according to Edmonds. While his Vietnam-battered brother was an emotional catalyst, Gaye had neglected to send him one letter during his army stint. And though he was certainly aware of the Detroit race riot that left 43 people dead in 1967, he viewed the sad display on TV from his cushy home on the outskirts of town. Not to say Gaye didn’t wholeheartedly believe in the progressive observations found on What’s Going On, but his relative distance from his subjects allows him to fly over top of them, providing a healing pulse to the disarray below.

description.plain:
From Gaye’s 1976 album I Want You. This song was groundbreaking music, with some of the most controversial lyrics of its time, “Soon” was inspired by Marvin’s then-wife Janis, who he mentions in the song.

Throughout the song, Marvin works towards his revelation that he’ll “soon” be committing his love to his woman by performing oral sex on her. He continues in that vein, singing of how much he relishes the thought of giving Janis “head” for the first time, sanctifying the idea by invoking marriage and pregnancy, promising to “knock her up” and create a family together.

“Soon” saw a resurgence in popularity following its sampling in Jay-Z’s 2007 hit “American Dreaming”.
